00:00:22.310 --> 00:00:24.060
PROFESSOR: OK if there
are no questions,

00:00:24.060 --> 00:00:25.430
we will get back to physics.

00:00:25.430 --> 00:00:33.240
What I want to do today, as
it suggests on the slide,

00:00:33.240 --> 00:00:36.855
is to finish the kinematics
of homogeneous expansion

00:00:36.855 --> 00:00:38.905
that we were talking
about last time.

00:00:38.905 --> 00:00:42.176
And the one topic in that
category that we have not

00:00:42.176 --> 00:00:44.496
discussed yet is the
cosmological redshift

00:00:44.496 --> 00:00:46.910
So we'll begin by
going over that.

00:00:46.910 --> 00:00:50.670
And then we'll begin to go on
to the next topic altogether,

00:00:50.670 --> 00:00:53.645
which is the dynamics of
homogeneous expansion --

00:00:53.645 --> 00:00:57.573
how do we understand how
gravity affects the expansion

00:00:57.573 --> 00:00:58.555
of the universe?

00:00:58.555 --> 00:01:01.712
So that will be the main
subject of today's lecture,

00:01:01.712 --> 00:01:06.457
once we've finished up the issue
of the cosmological redshift

00:01:06.457 --> 00:01:07.680
shift.

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:11.292
Let me remind you that at
end of the last lecture,

00:01:11.292 --> 00:01:14.274
we were talking about the
synchronization of clocks,

00:01:14.274 --> 00:01:16.262
and the coordinate
system that we'll

00:01:16.262 --> 00:01:18.910
be using to describe the
homogeneously expanding

00:01:18.910 --> 00:01:22.150
model of the universe.

00:01:22.150 --> 00:01:24.980
Remember, we are introducing
spatial coordinates

00:01:24.980 --> 00:01:28.853
that grow with the
universe, so that we're

00:01:28.853 --> 00:01:31.436
going to be assuming the fact,
literally, that the universe is

00:01:31.436 --> 00:01:33.186
perfectly homogeneous
and isotropic, which

00:01:33.186 --> 00:01:35.864
means that all objects will
be literally addressed,

00:01:35.864 --> 00:01:37.833
relative to this
coordinate system.

00:01:37.833 --> 00:01:40.240
If we're talking about
the real universe,

00:01:40.240 --> 00:01:42.646
then there would be
some motion relative

00:01:42.646 --> 00:01:45.940
to this coordinate system,
because the universe is not

00:01:45.940 --> 00:01:47.513
exactly homogeneous.

00:01:47.513 --> 00:01:50.013
But we're going to be working
for now with the approximation

00:01:50.013 --> 00:01:52.713
that our model universe is
exactly homogeneous, which

00:01:52.713 --> 00:01:54.432
means that all
matter is completely

00:01:54.432 --> 00:01:58.730
at rest, relative to this
expanding coordinate system.

00:01:58.730 --> 00:02:00.771
And now we want to talk
about how to define time,

00:02:00.771 --> 00:02:02.437
or to review what we
said last time when

00:02:02.437 --> 00:02:04.590
we talked about
how to define time.

00:02:04.590 --> 00:02:07.625
What we will imagine is that in
every location in the universe

00:02:07.625 --> 00:02:11.070
at rest, relative to
the matter, is a clock.

00:02:11.070 --> 00:02:15.835
And each clock ticks off
time, and all those clocks

00:02:15.835 --> 00:02:19.144
will be acceptable
as a clock which

00:02:19.144 --> 00:02:22.976
measures the time at
relevant positions-- time

00:02:22.976 --> 00:02:25.210
is measured locally--
but we still

00:02:25.210 --> 00:02:27.780
have to talk about
synchronizing those clocks.

00:02:27.780 --> 00:02:30.440
And what we said last time
is that we can synchronize

00:02:30.440 --> 00:02:33.836
the clocks as long as there's
some cosmic phenomena that

00:02:33.836 --> 00:02:37.098
can be seen everywhere, which
has some time evolution.

00:02:37.098 --> 00:02:40.237
And we gave two examples-- one
is the evolution of the Hubble

00:02:40.237 --> 00:02:43.510
expansion rate, which
can be measured locally,

00:02:43.510 --> 00:02:47.795
and everybody can agree to set
their clocks to midnight when

00:02:47.795 --> 00:02:51.530
the Hubble expansion
rate has a certain value.

00:02:51.530 --> 00:02:55.347
And another cosmic
variable is the temperature

00:02:55.347 --> 00:02:58.784
of the cosmic microwave
background radiation.

00:02:58.784 --> 00:03:01.239
So, everybody in
this model universe

00:03:01.239 --> 00:03:04.185
will agree that we'll set
the clocks to midnight when

00:03:04.185 --> 00:03:06.640
the temperature of the
cosmic background radiation

00:03:06.640 --> 00:03:10.570
goes to 5 degrees, or
any specified number.

00:03:10.570 --> 00:03:13.060
So as long as there's a
phenomena of that sort, which

00:03:13.060 --> 00:03:16.670
there is in our universe,
it's possible to synchronize

00:03:16.670 --> 00:03:18.349
these clocks in a unique way.

00:03:18.349 --> 00:03:19.765
And the important
thing to realize

00:03:19.765 --> 00:03:22.018
is that once they're
synchronized at one time,

00:03:22.018 --> 00:03:24.463
they will remain
synchronized as a consequence

00:03:24.463 --> 00:03:27.397
of our assumption
of homogeneity.

00:03:27.397 --> 00:03:30.331
That is, if everybody agrees
that the cosmic background

00:03:30.331 --> 00:03:33.620
radiation has a temperature
of 10 degrees at midnight,

00:03:33.620 --> 00:03:38.130
if everybody waits for 15
minutes after midnight,

00:03:38.130 --> 00:03:40.390
everybody should see the
same fall in temperature

00:03:40.390 --> 00:03:42.670
during that time
interval, otherwise

00:03:42.670 --> 00:03:44.736
it would be a violation
of this hypothesis

00:03:44.736 --> 00:03:46.668
of perfect homogeneity.

00:03:46.668 --> 00:03:48.117
Yes, question.

00:03:48.117 --> 00:03:51.015
AUDIENCE: Is it verified
that temperature

00:03:51.015 --> 00:03:55.879
is invariant for all observers--
all Lorentz observers?

00:03:55.879 --> 00:03:58.170
PROFESSOR: OK the question
is, is temperature invariant

00:03:58.170 --> 00:03:59.325
for all observers?

00:03:59.325 --> 00:04:04.020
And the question even included
all Lorentz observers.

00:04:04.020 --> 00:04:07.497
It's not really invariant to
different Lorentz observers.

00:04:07.497 --> 00:04:10.163
We're talking about a privileged
class of observers, all of whom

00:04:10.163 --> 00:04:12.570
are at rest, relative
to the average matter.

00:04:12.570 --> 00:04:14.950
If you move through the
cosmic background radiation,

00:04:14.950 --> 00:04:18.249
then you don't see uniform
thermal distribution any more.

00:04:18.249 --> 00:04:20.209
Rather what you see
is radiation that's

00:04:20.209 --> 00:04:22.066
hotter in the forward
direction and colder

00:04:22.066 --> 00:04:23.149
in the backward direction.

00:04:23.149 --> 00:04:25.599
And we in fact, as I think
I have mentioned here,

00:04:25.599 --> 00:04:28.049
see that effect in
our real universe.

00:04:28.049 --> 00:04:31.390
We're apparently moving relative
to the cosmic background

00:04:31.390 --> 00:04:35.678
radiation, at about 1/1000th
of the speed of light.

00:04:35.678 --> 00:04:40.929
So it's not invariant
with respect to motion.

00:04:40.929 --> 00:04:42.720
There's the additional
question, though is,

00:04:42.720 --> 00:04:46.240
is it the same everywhere
in the visible universe?

00:04:46.240 --> 00:04:48.650
As far as we can tell, it is.

00:04:48.650 --> 00:04:51.750
There is some direct measurement
of that, that we'll probably

00:04:51.750 --> 00:04:54.310
talk about later in
the course, by looking

00:04:54.310 --> 00:04:57.350
at certain spectral lines
in distant galaxies.

00:04:57.350 --> 00:04:59.724
One can effectively
measure the temperature

00:04:59.724 --> 00:05:01.140
of the cosmic
microwave background

00:05:01.140 --> 00:05:03.442
radiation in some
distant galaxies.

00:05:03.442 --> 00:05:05.150
This line cannot be
seen in all galaxies,

00:05:05.150 --> 00:05:09.027
and the extent that it's
been measured in degrees.

00:05:09.027 --> 00:05:10.610
So certainly in our
model, we're going

00:05:10.610 --> 00:05:12.720
to assume complete homogeneity,
so everything's the same

00:05:12.720 --> 00:05:15.515
everywhere, and there is strong
evidence for that homogeneity.

00:05:15.515 --> 00:05:17.530
Although it's not
exact, but there's

00:05:17.530 --> 00:05:20.040
strong evidence for
approximate homogeneity

00:05:20.040 --> 00:05:22.438
in the real universe.

00:05:22.438 --> 00:05:22.938
Yes?

00:05:22.938 --> 00:05:24.399
AUDIENCE: If you were really
close to the black hole

00:05:24.399 --> 00:05:24.899
[INAUDIBLE].

00:05:34.847 --> 00:05:35.430
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:05:35.430 --> 00:05:37.820
The question is, suppose we're
a little bit more careful,

00:05:37.820 --> 00:05:40.210
and talk about the fact that
some people might be living

00:05:40.210 --> 00:05:42.980
near black holes, and
other people are not.

00:05:42.980 --> 00:05:45.080
Will that affect the
synchronization of clocks

00:05:45.080 --> 00:05:47.100
for the people who are
living near black holes?

00:05:47.100 --> 00:05:49.580
The answer is sure, it will.

00:05:49.580 --> 00:05:53.410
We can only synchronize
clocks cosmically

00:05:53.410 --> 00:05:56.825
if we assume that the universe
is absolutely homogeneous.

00:05:56.825 --> 00:05:58.740
As soon as you introduce
inhomogeneities

00:05:58.740 --> 00:06:01.530
like black holes, or even
just stars like the sun,

00:06:01.530 --> 00:06:04.250
they create small
perturbations, which

00:06:04.250 --> 00:06:06.450
then make it really
impossible to expect clocks

00:06:06.450 --> 00:06:09.160
to stay in sync with each other.

00:06:09.160 --> 00:06:11.510
So as soon as you have
concentrations of mass,

00:06:11.510 --> 00:06:13.810
then the fact that what
we're talking about now

00:06:13.810 --> 00:06:17.220
is an approximation
becomes real.

00:06:17.220 --> 00:06:19.569
But those deviations are small.

00:06:19.569 --> 00:06:20.985
The deviations
coming from the sun

00:06:20.985 --> 00:06:24.660
are only on the order of
a part in a million or so.

00:06:24.660 --> 00:06:28.310
So, to a very good
approximation,

00:06:28.310 --> 00:06:30.970
the universe obeys
what we're describing,

00:06:30.970 --> 00:06:34.004
although if you went very
close to the surface of one

00:06:34.004 --> 00:06:35.420
of these super-massive
black holes

00:06:35.420 --> 00:06:37.290
in the centers of
galaxies, or something,

00:06:37.290 --> 00:06:39.070
you would in fact
find they had a very

00:06:39.070 --> 00:06:42.082
significant effect
on your clocks.

00:06:42.082 --> 00:06:42.915
Any other questions?

00:06:45.420 --> 00:06:46.290
OK.

00:06:46.290 --> 00:06:48.270
Let me move on now.

00:06:48.270 --> 00:06:51.760
The next topic, as
I have warned you,

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:54.063
is the cosmological redshift.

00:06:54.063 --> 00:06:59.899
Now in the first lecture
beyond the overview,

00:06:59.899 --> 00:07:02.190
which I guess was a combination
of the second and third

00:07:02.190 --> 00:07:05.730
lectures in the course, we
talked about the Doppler shift

00:07:05.730 --> 00:07:08.720
for sound waves, and we talked
about the relativistic Doppler

00:07:08.720 --> 00:07:10.990
shift for light
waves-- that was all

00:07:10.990 --> 00:07:13.680
in the context of
special relativity.

00:07:13.680 --> 00:07:15.470
Now what we're going
to face is the fact

00:07:15.470 --> 00:07:18.510
that cosmology is not
really governed entirely

00:07:18.510 --> 00:07:22.700
by special relativity, although
special relativity still

00:07:22.700 --> 00:07:26.365
holds locally in our cosmology.

00:07:26.365 --> 00:07:29.480
But special relativity does not
include the effects of gravity,

00:07:29.480 --> 00:07:31.440
and on a global scale,
the effects of gravity

00:07:31.440 --> 00:07:33.660
are very important
for cosmology,

00:07:33.660 --> 00:07:35.410
and therefore special
relativity by itself

00:07:35.410 --> 00:07:41.290
is not enough to understand
many properties of the universe,

00:07:41.290 --> 00:07:44.026
including the
cosmological redshift.

00:07:44.026 --> 00:07:45.400
It turns out
though, that there's

00:07:45.400 --> 00:07:47.525
a way of describing the
cosmological redshift which

00:07:47.525 --> 00:07:50.030
will make it sound even simpler
than special relativity.

00:07:50.030 --> 00:07:51.680
And I'll describe
that first, and then

00:07:51.680 --> 00:07:53.138
afterwards, we'll
talk a little bit

00:07:53.138 --> 00:07:58.210
about how this very
simple-looking derivation jives

00:07:58.210 --> 00:08:01.160
with the special relativity
derivation, which must also

00:08:01.160 --> 00:08:04.730
be correct, at least locally.

00:08:04.730 --> 00:08:05.620
OK.

00:08:05.620 --> 00:08:13.040
So, the question we
want to ask ourselves,

00:08:13.040 --> 00:08:16.660
is suppose we look
at a distant galaxy,

00:08:16.660 --> 00:08:19.820
and light is emitted
from that galaxy.

00:08:19.820 --> 00:08:22.010
How will the frequency
of that light

00:08:22.010 --> 00:08:26.830
shift between the frequency
it had when it was emitted,

00:08:26.830 --> 00:08:28.500
and the frequency
that we would measure

00:08:28.500 --> 00:08:30.690
as we received the light.

00:08:30.690 --> 00:08:37.039
So to draw the situation on
the blackboard, let's introduce

00:08:37.039 --> 00:08:39.450
a coordinate system, x.

00:08:39.450 --> 00:08:41.515
And this will be our
comoving coordinate system.

00:08:41.515 --> 00:08:44.340
X is measured in notches.

00:08:44.340 --> 00:08:51.860
We'll put ourselves at
the origin-- there is us.

00:08:51.860 --> 00:08:55.100
And we'll put our
galaxy out here

00:08:55.100 --> 00:09:02.470
someplace-- there is the
distant galaxy that we

00:09:02.470 --> 00:09:04.880
will be observing.

00:09:04.880 --> 00:09:09.240
They galaxy will be at some
particular coordinate, which

00:09:09.240 --> 00:09:13.600
I will call l sub c, c
for coordinate distance,

00:09:13.600 --> 00:09:18.210
so l sub c is the coordinate
distance to the galaxy.

00:09:18.210 --> 00:09:21.930
And then the physical
distance-- is

00:09:21.930 --> 00:09:25.010
what we've been calling
l sub p, p for physical,

00:09:25.010 --> 00:09:29.330
which depends on time, because
there's Hubble expansion.

00:09:29.330 --> 00:09:34.255
So l sub p of t, as we've said
a number of times already,

00:09:34.255 --> 00:09:38.810
is a of t times l sub c.

00:09:38.810 --> 00:09:41.690
The scale factor, which
depends on time, times

00:09:41.690 --> 00:09:44.520
the coordinate distance,
which does not depend on time.

00:09:44.520 --> 00:09:49.960
So everything just expands
with the scale factor a of t.

00:09:49.960 --> 00:09:56.950
So this describes the
situation, and now

00:09:56.950 --> 00:09:58.830
what we want to
ask ourselves, is

00:09:58.830 --> 00:10:03.860
suppose a wave is being
emitted by the galaxy--

00:10:03.860 --> 00:10:06.800
and we'll be trying to track
the distance between wave

00:10:06.800 --> 00:10:10.800
crests, which determines
what the wavelength is.

00:10:10.800 --> 00:10:15.220
Since we'll only be
interested in wave crests,

00:10:15.220 --> 00:10:18.270
we will talk in
language where we just

00:10:18.270 --> 00:10:19.885
imagine there's a
pulse at each crest,

00:10:19.885 --> 00:10:21.343
and what happens
in between doesn't

00:10:21.343 --> 00:10:23.710
matter for what
we're talking about.

00:10:23.710 --> 00:10:32.210
So we want to track successive
pulses emitted by the galaxy.

00:10:32.210 --> 00:10:37.330
Now the important
feature of our system

00:10:37.330 --> 00:10:40.650
is that we have
argued that we know

00:10:40.650 --> 00:10:47.160
how to track light waves through
this kind of coordinate system.

00:10:47.160 --> 00:10:52.940
If x is our cosmic coordinate,
dx dt, the coordinate velocity

00:10:52.940 --> 00:10:57.900
of light, is just equal to the
ordinary velocity of light,

00:10:57.900 --> 00:11:03.210
c, but rescaled by
the scale factor.

00:11:03.210 --> 00:11:04.890
And the scale factor
here is playing

00:11:04.890 --> 00:11:07.660
the role of converting
meters to notches.

00:11:07.660 --> 00:11:10.370
So c is measured in
meters per second.

00:11:10.370 --> 00:11:12.570
By dividing by a of
t, we get the speed

00:11:12.570 --> 00:11:14.840
in notches per second,
which is what we want,

00:11:14.840 --> 00:11:18.045
because x is measured, not
in meters, but in notches.

00:11:18.045 --> 00:11:21.870
A notch being the arbitrary
coordinate-- the arbitrary unit

00:11:21.870 --> 00:11:26.180
that we adopt to describe our
comoving coordinate system.

00:11:29.330 --> 00:11:31.600
Now the important
feature of this equation,

00:11:31.600 --> 00:11:36.010
for our current purpose, is that
the speed of light, as we're

00:11:36.010 --> 00:11:38.300
going to follow
these light pulses

00:11:38.300 --> 00:11:42.480
through our coordinate
system, depends on time,

00:11:42.480 --> 00:11:45.140
but it does not depend on x.

00:11:45.140 --> 00:11:49.280
Our universe is homogeneous,
so all points x are the same.

00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:53.140
So two pulses will travel at
the same speed at the same time,

00:11:53.140 --> 00:11:55.540
no matter where they are.

00:11:55.540 --> 00:11:58.350
And that's all we really
need, to understand

00:11:58.350 --> 00:12:02.680
the fact that if one
pulse leaves our galaxy

00:12:02.680 --> 00:12:04.868
and is coming towards
us-- I should do that

00:12:04.868 --> 00:12:07.076
with my right hand, because
the second pulse is going

00:12:07.076 --> 00:12:11.280
to be my other hand-- as
that second pulse follows it,

00:12:11.280 --> 00:12:13.347
the second pulse,
at any given time--

00:12:13.347 --> 00:12:15.180
even though the speed
will change with time,

00:12:15.180 --> 00:12:17.650
but at any given
time-- the second pulse

00:12:17.650 --> 00:12:20.310
will be traveling at the same
speed as the first pulse.

00:12:20.310 --> 00:12:25.050
And that means that it'll
look something like this.

00:12:25.050 --> 00:12:26.541
The speed might
change with time,

00:12:26.541 --> 00:12:28.915
but as long as they both travel
at exactly the same speed

00:12:28.915 --> 00:12:32.150
at any given time, they will
stay exactly the same distance

00:12:32.150 --> 00:12:35.440
apart in our comoving
coordinate system.

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:39.080
Delta x, the x distance
between the two pulses,

00:12:39.080 --> 00:12:41.040
will not change with time.

00:12:41.040 --> 00:12:44.600
And if the coordinate distance
does not change with time--

00:12:44.600 --> 00:12:47.400
the physical distance is
always the scale factor

00:12:47.400 --> 00:12:49.440
times the coordinate
distance-- it

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:52.120
means that the physical
wavelength of the light pulse

00:12:52.120 --> 00:12:54.820
will simply be stretched
with the scale factor, which

00:12:54.820 --> 00:12:57.500
means you'll be stretched with
the expansion of the universe,

00:12:57.500 --> 00:13:01.230
in exactly the same way as any
other distance in this model

00:13:01.230 --> 00:13:04.990
universe will be stretched
as the universe expands.

00:13:04.990 --> 00:13:07.300
So that's the key idea,
and it's very simple,

00:13:07.300 --> 00:13:09.435
and those words
really say it all.

00:13:12.640 --> 00:13:23.990
Delta x equals constant
implies delta l

00:13:23.990 --> 00:13:31.770
physical is
proportional to a of t,

00:13:31.770 --> 00:13:37.240
and that implies that the
wavelength of the light,

00:13:37.240 --> 00:13:40.890
as a function of t, is
proportional to a of t.

00:13:43.480 --> 00:13:46.630
Wavelength is actually what I
was calling delta l physical,

00:13:46.630 --> 00:13:48.771
the distance between
these two pulses,

00:13:48.771 --> 00:13:51.870
where each pulse represents
a crest of the wave.

00:13:51.870 --> 00:13:55.310
And lambda is the standard
letter of the wavelength.

00:14:22.680 --> 00:14:26.380
Now the wavelength is related
to the period of a wave

00:14:26.380 --> 00:14:28.580
simply by the
relationship that lambda

00:14:28.580 --> 00:14:32.770
is equal to c times delta t.

00:14:32.770 --> 00:14:37.490
Wavelength is just the distance
the wave travels in one period.

00:14:37.490 --> 00:14:40.480
So if lambda is
proportional to a of t,

00:14:40.480 --> 00:14:44.360
so is the time interval, delta
t, the period of the wave,

00:14:44.360 --> 00:14:46.610
going to be
proportional to delta t.

00:14:46.610 --> 00:14:48.480
So we have been
defining the redshift

00:14:48.480 --> 00:14:50.500
in terms of the period.

00:14:50.500 --> 00:14:59.800
So delta t observed over
delta t at the source

00:14:59.800 --> 00:15:11.355
is equal to lambda observed
over lambda at the source.

00:15:14.869 --> 00:15:18.680
Lambda and delta t are
proportional to each other.

00:15:18.680 --> 00:15:20.650
And-- let me finish and
I'll get to you, OK?

00:15:20.650 --> 00:15:21.400
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:15:21.400 --> 00:15:23.850
PROFESSOR: This then,
the ratio of the lengths,

00:15:23.850 --> 00:15:25.350
is just the amount
by which universe

00:15:25.350 --> 00:15:27.590
has stretched over that time.

00:15:27.590 --> 00:15:30.720
So just the ratio of the scale
factors at the two times.

00:15:30.720 --> 00:15:35.330
So this is equal to just a of
the time of observation, which

00:15:35.330 --> 00:15:41.785
I'll call t sub o, over a of
the time of the source, t sub s.

00:15:44.998 --> 00:15:54.590
So this is the scale
factor at source,

00:15:54.590 --> 00:16:04.175
and the numerator here is the
scale factor at observation.

00:16:09.040 --> 00:16:11.710
And this ratio of times,
or ratio of wavelengths,

00:16:11.710 --> 00:16:15.350
or ratio of scale factors,
is defined to be 1 plus z,

00:16:15.350 --> 00:16:16.620
as we have always done.

00:16:16.620 --> 00:16:19.130
The ratio of the time intervals
we had defined originally

00:16:19.130 --> 00:16:21.920
as 1 plus z, we'll
keep that definition,

00:16:21.920 --> 00:16:24.909
and that defines the
redshift shift, z.

00:16:24.909 --> 00:16:25.450
Question now?

00:16:25.450 --> 00:16:26.436
Yes.

00:16:26.436 --> 00:16:28.420
AUDIENCE: Is that
