00:17:45.930 --> 00:17:47.570
How does this relate
to what we already

00:17:47.570 --> 00:17:50.075
said about the redshift?

00:17:57.570 --> 00:18:00.420
This answer-- I would like
to quantify things and say

00:18:00.420 --> 00:18:02.481
that it differs in two
ways from the calculation

00:18:02.481 --> 00:18:03.605
that we've done previously.

00:18:29.850 --> 00:18:34.330
And the first is-- the
reason why it's important

00:18:34.330 --> 00:18:37.750
to us-- is that this actually
takes into account, effects

00:18:37.750 --> 00:18:40.050
which were not taken into
account by our earlier

00:18:40.050 --> 00:18:41.430
calculation.

00:18:41.430 --> 00:18:43.520
In particular, even
though we derived this

00:18:43.520 --> 00:18:47.920
by a very simple
kinematic argument, which

00:18:47.920 --> 00:18:50.890
didn't seem to involve
much math at all,

00:18:50.890 --> 00:18:53.430
it actually is
incredibly strong,

00:18:53.430 --> 00:18:59.610
in that it encompasses not only
special relativity, but also

00:18:59.610 --> 00:19:00.680
general relativity.

00:19:00.680 --> 00:19:02.609
It includes all the
effects of gravity.

00:19:02.609 --> 00:19:04.150
If you think about
what gravity might

00:19:04.150 --> 00:19:06.750
do to what we're
talking about, gravity

00:19:06.750 --> 00:19:10.320
doesn't change the fact
that the speed of light

00:19:10.320 --> 00:19:12.135
is going to be c over a of t.

00:19:12.135 --> 00:19:14.450
That really is just
a unit conversion,

00:19:14.450 --> 00:19:16.790
combined with the fundamental
physics assumption

00:19:16.790 --> 00:19:18.165
that the speed of
light is always

00:19:18.165 --> 00:19:22.480
measured at c, relative
to any observer.

00:19:22.480 --> 00:19:25.210
So when we put in
gravity, this relationship

00:19:25.210 --> 00:19:26.780
continues to hold--
that was really

00:19:26.780 --> 00:19:29.329
all we used to drive
this-- so gravity is not

00:19:29.329 --> 00:19:30.792
going to affect the answer.

00:19:30.792 --> 00:19:32.945
If you think about
special relativity,

00:19:32.945 --> 00:19:34.460
is there something left out?

00:19:34.460 --> 00:19:36.153
Everything I said
here, Newton would

00:19:36.153 --> 00:19:37.236
have understood perfectly.

00:19:37.236 --> 00:19:39.111
I didn't have to mention
time dilation, which

00:19:39.111 --> 00:19:42.490
was crucial to our special
relativity calculation

00:19:42.490 --> 00:19:43.841
of the redshift shift.

00:19:43.841 --> 00:19:44.715
Did I make a mistake?

00:19:44.715 --> 00:19:48.760
Is there some place where time
dilation should come in here?

00:19:48.760 --> 00:19:52.140
The answer, really, is
no, if you think about it.

00:19:52.140 --> 00:19:54.555
We had two clocks
involved in our system,

00:19:54.555 --> 00:19:59.850
a clock on the galaxy,
and a clock at us,

00:19:59.850 --> 00:20:03.020
which we used to measure
the period of emission,

00:20:03.020 --> 00:20:08.500
and the period of reception, but
those clocks are each at rest,

00:20:08.500 --> 00:20:10.300
relative to matter
in the region--

00:20:10.300 --> 00:20:13.760
even though they're moving
with respect to each other--

00:20:13.760 --> 00:20:18.552
so by definition, they
do measure cosmic time.

00:20:18.552 --> 00:20:20.385
Cosmic time is a very
peculiar kind of time,

00:20:20.385 --> 00:20:22.120
it's not the time in
any inertial frame.

00:20:22.120 --> 00:20:24.260
These clocks are moving
with respect to each other,

00:20:24.260 --> 00:20:27.434
so if you were defining
inertial frame time,

00:20:27.434 --> 00:20:29.100
their clocks could
never be synchronized

00:20:29.100 --> 00:20:31.950
and would never agree
with each other.

00:20:31.950 --> 00:20:34.800
But in this concept
of cosmic time,

00:20:34.800 --> 00:20:39.100
they do agree with each
other, by construction.

00:20:39.100 --> 00:20:42.170
And since each clock is at rest,
relative to its local matter,

00:20:42.170 --> 00:20:44.450
it measures this t that
we're talking about,

00:20:44.450 --> 00:20:47.180
this cosmic time variable.

00:20:47.180 --> 00:20:51.970
And when the pulse
arrives at us,

00:20:51.970 --> 00:20:55.486
when we measure
delta t on our clock,

00:20:55.486 --> 00:20:57.360
that's exactly the
quantity that, in the end,

00:20:57.360 --> 00:21:00.642
we want to talk about--
delta t sub observer.

00:21:00.642 --> 00:21:02.380
The quantity measured
on our clock,

00:21:02.380 --> 00:21:05.450
which is a clock which
also measures cosmic time.

00:21:05.450 --> 00:21:07.784
So there's no place for
any time dilation to enter.

00:21:07.784 --> 00:21:10.000
It's not that we forgot
it, it's not there.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:12.320
It's not part of
this calculation.

00:21:12.320 --> 00:21:15.200
So this result, as
simple as it looks,

00:21:15.200 --> 00:21:17.190
actually fully
encompasses the effects

00:21:17.190 --> 00:21:20.490
of both special
relativity and gravity.

00:21:20.490 --> 00:21:22.470
Now let me just mention,
it's not obvious

00:21:22.470 --> 00:21:23.600
how gravity came in here.

00:21:23.600 --> 00:21:26.960
I'm telling you it
satisfies-- includes

00:21:26.960 --> 00:21:28.260
all the effects of gravity.

00:21:28.260 --> 00:21:29.580
Where is gravity hidden?

00:21:29.580 --> 00:21:32.160
Let me throw that
