00:21:32.160 --> 00:21:34.450
How does gravity affect
this calculation,

00:21:34.450 --> 00:21:37.210
even though I didn't
have to mention gravity

00:21:37.210 --> 00:21:38.971
when I described
the calculation?

00:21:38.971 --> 00:21:40.294
Yeah, in back.

00:21:40.294 --> 00:21:41.620
AUDIENCE: The scale factor?

00:21:41.620 --> 00:21:42.570
PROFESSOR: That's
right, the scale factor.

00:21:42.570 --> 00:21:45.090
We have not yet talked
about how a of t evolves.

00:21:45.090 --> 00:21:47.880
And the evolution of the
a of t will explicitly

00:21:47.880 --> 00:21:49.640
involve the effects of gravity.

00:21:49.640 --> 00:21:52.405
And that's why this
result depends on gravity,

00:21:52.405 --> 00:21:56.210
even though we didn't
need to use gravity,

00:21:56.210 --> 00:22:00.030
or say anything about
gravity to get the results.

00:22:00.030 --> 00:22:03.200
So this is the first difference.

00:22:03.200 --> 00:22:13.690
This calculation includes
the effect of gravity.

00:22:22.867 --> 00:22:24.960
Which is through a of t.

00:22:31.170 --> 00:22:34.380
Now, because this calculation
seems to include everything

00:22:34.380 --> 00:22:36.400
that the first calculation
included and more,

00:22:36.400 --> 00:22:37.899
you'd expect to be
more complicated,

00:22:37.899 --> 00:22:40.382
but it's less complicated.

00:22:40.382 --> 00:22:41.840
Could we have saved
ourselves a lot

00:22:41.840 --> 00:22:43.923
of time last week by just
giving this calculation,

00:22:43.923 --> 00:22:46.105
and deriving the
other answer from it.

00:22:46.105 --> 00:22:49.940
The answer is, not easily,
it would not have saved time,

00:22:49.940 --> 00:22:51.607
one can't, in principle,
do it that way.

00:22:51.607 --> 00:22:53.023
But the other
important difference

00:22:53.023 --> 00:22:55.110
between these two
calculations is the variables

00:22:55.110 --> 00:22:57.930
that you're using to
express your answer.

00:22:57.930 --> 00:23:01.369
Once you ask a question, if
you ask the question vaguely,

00:23:01.369 --> 00:23:03.660
there could be many different
answers to that question,

00:23:03.660 --> 00:23:08.120
depending on what variables
are used to express the answer.

00:23:08.120 --> 00:23:22.300
So what we're doing here is
we're expressing the redshift z

00:23:22.300 --> 00:23:29.000
for objects which are in fact at
rest in the comoving coordinate

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:29.500
system.

00:23:43.880 --> 00:23:56.715
The special relativity
calculation-- I think I'm

00:23:56.715 --> 00:23:58.090
going to need
another blackboard.

00:24:02.730 --> 00:24:17.240
The special relativity
calculation, on the other hand

00:24:17.240 --> 00:24:32.300
gives z as a function
of the velocity,

00:24:32.300 --> 00:24:37.070
as measured in an inertial
coordinate system.

00:24:46.316 --> 00:24:47.940
So the answers are
just being expressed

00:24:47.940 --> 00:24:50.010
in terms of totally
different things,

00:24:50.010 --> 00:24:51.969
and the answer is so
simple here because a of t

00:24:51.969 --> 00:24:53.718
already incorporates
a lot of information,

00:24:53.718 --> 00:24:55.410
and we've just taken
advantage of that

00:24:55.410 --> 00:24:58.694
to be able to give a very simple
answer in terms of a of t,

00:24:58.694 --> 00:25:02.520
without yet saying how we're
